Prologue
"Please, I beg you!" pleaded Queen Eirwen, "don't send her away! She's still a child!" The Ice King, accompanied by his royal advisor, looked down from his throne at his wife. She had given birth to a girl. At the thought of this, his expression darkened.
The girl resembled her mother very much. She had pale blue eyes and white hair with blue streaks. A girl meant weakness in the eyes of the Ice King. After all, up until this point he had only fathered sons.
"You have two choices: Either you kill the child or you send it into the wilderness. That is its punishment for your failure, Eirwen." He spat out her name as if it were poisonous. He always did this.
Frostfell had not always been a single kingdom. Previously, it consisted of two parts, the North and the South. In the North lay the non-magical kingdom, while the South was a kingdom full of fantastic powers. But the North showed its greed and there came an endless war between the two kingdoms, until finally the South offered a ceasefire.
The desperation in the South was so great that the royal family was willing to do anything to end the bloodshed. They offered to send their only princess as queen to the North, where she was to give birth to a son, the future king. In this case, the North would unite with the South to form a single kingdom. The North accepted the proposal and Princess Eirwen married Prince Akull.
"I beg you, my king, do with me whatever you wish, lock me up, banish me or kill me, but spare my child," pleaded Queen Eirwen, holding her child in her arms.
The Ice King looked down on his queen with full disdain. Perhaps, but only perhaps, he would have mercy on her. With the woman who had been his wife for 22 years, who had stood by him in his worst times and who had given him his sons.
"Alright. The child can remain in the palace," he said, which the queen acknowledged with a sigh. "But," he added, "you will be executed."
The royal advisor and Queen Eirwen looked at each other in horror. Slowly, she turned her gaze to the floor. "Yes, my king." She bowed.
The Ice King ordered the royal advisor to take the queen's daughter to one of Eirwen's empty rooms. Then he ordered the guards to take Eirwen to the execution ground, where all the citizens of the city could watch.
As the guards escorted her to the execution ground, a loud uproar broke out among the citizens when they realized that their only beloved queen was going to be executed. Some people cried, others shouted and attacked the guards. Others still asked themselves why this was happening, but all were in agreement.
"Let her go!"
"Why are they doing this to her?"
As Eirwen approached the wooden stake, the most feared person in the kingdom appeared. The executioner. The woman who had just been a queen was to be burned. No one deserved such a death, not even criminals. It was the worst thing that could be done to a person in Frostfell.
Eirwen was tied to the wooden stake, and the king declared in a speech how the queen had betrayed them all. The inhabitants of Frostfell refused to believe the king and would not accept his words. Then the executioner lit the wooden stake on fire, and a single tear rolled down the face of the former queen.
"Don't give up, Kari." This was the end of Queen Eirwen's reign.
Dead silence in the palace
Only a knock could be heard from the room located all the way to the left in the south wing of the eternally cold palace. The servants who passed by always wondered what was in that room. They were afraid of it. In the palace, rumors spread among the maids. Allegedly, the deceased wife of the Ice King, Eirwen, was in this room and was waiting to be let out.
Her assumption could not have been more wrong, thought Ivory as she headed toward the south wing, while the servants walked around and whispered to each other. They had no idea what was hiding behind the door.
The rumors concerned Ivory as well, since Ivory was the only one allowed to enter the room.
Knock, knock. "Lady Kari, are you in there?" whispered Ivory in front of the intricately decorated door, adorned with snowflakes and a crown, the symbol of the royal family.
Ivory wondered if—unlike last time—she would actually be allowed entry. I still have bruises from last time. Ivory giggled at the thought. Kari had thrown a book against Ivory's shoulder, but immediately apologized when she realized who she had hit.
A single knock could be heard from inside, probably to say that she was there. Where else should she be?
"May I come in?" asked Ivory. In the past, Ivory had walked in without asking.
From inside, Ivory heard a knock. That probably meant a "Yes." The cold and the sound made Ivory shiver. It felt strange to hear a sound from a supposedly empty room, although Ivory had been going in there for several years now.
"I'm coming in," said Ivory and slowly opened the door. The sight that Ivory saw in the room was unusual for normal people, but not unexpected for Ivory. Paper was everywhere. Books were scattered around, the desk was broken, and several ice sculptures lay around. There were no windows and little to no light. Moreover, it was colder than the rest of the palace (which said a lot). The room looked as if a snowstorm had swept through it.
The girl was curled up in her bed, wrapped in her bedsheet, and was reading in one of her notebooks. A small lantern illuminated the room.
"Which notebook is that?" asked Ivory and sat down next to Kari on the bed.
